Inference part II: t tests and inference in regression

Introduction

This week well look at inference for continuous variables and how to analyse them in R. Well cover:

  • One sample t-test
  • Two sample/ independent sample t test
  • Inference in our regression output

Rs family of distribution functions: comparing the normal and t distributions

Last week we saw how to use the various binom functions, including rbinom to get random draws from the binomial distribution, dbinom to get the probability of an event on the binomial distribution and pbinom to get the sum of probabilities under the curve.

R uses different versions of the same thing for other distributions. Lets compare the t and normal distributions to see how each works.

Well sample from each of them and compare. Recall from the lecture:

  • The point of the t distribution is: it can account for extra uncertainty when sample size is low. (It has longer tails when sample size is low.)
  • The t distributions only variable is degrees of freedom: for our tests here, thats just sample size minus one
  • The t distibution becomes like the normal distribution as sample size grows - they become close very quickly
  • The normal distribution only needs two numbers: the mean and standard deviation

Lets get some random samples from each and plot them over each other to see what difference sample size makes. Start with 3 degrees of freedom for a t distribution, equivalent to modelling a sample size of 4.

randomsamples_from_t <- rt(n = 100000, df = 3)

randomsamples_from_norm <- rnorm(n = 100000, mean = 0, sd = 1)

plot(density(randomsamples_from_norm))
lines(density(randomsamples_from_t), col='red')

EXERCISE: Change the t distibutions df argument (degrees of freedom) to see how quickly it starts to match the normal distributions shape. Try 10 then 100.

One-sample t test: do this class student grades differ from the regional average

This example is based on one from Danielle Navarros online book, which you can read at learningstatisticswithr.com/book. If you want to properly understand t tests Id highly recommend reading those sections.

for the first t-test, lets repeat the analysis from the lecture. Were doing the following:

  • Loading in 20 (fictional) student grades from a (fictional) class
  • Asking: do these grades differ from the (fictional) regional average for the same subject?

Lets load in the data first. Ive included the actual numbers in vector form, but you can just load in via URL. Also, well check the mean and standard deviation for the grades.

Well also set our fictional regional grade and assign to an object called meanofpopulation;

#Type in manually...
grades <- c(50,60,60,64,66,66,67,69,70,74,76,76,77,79,79,79,81,82,82,89)

#Or load them from the interwebnets
grades <- readRDS(url('https://bit.ly/smi106grades'))

mean(grades)
## [1] 72.3
sd(grades)
## [1] 9.520615
#Assumption of all class's grades
meanofpopulation <- 67.5

So we can see that the class and regional grades differ, but is the class grade really different from the regional grade? Can we be 95% sure? Our null hypothesis here is:

  • There is no difference between class and regional grade, or to put it another way;
  • The class and regional grades come from the same distribution

The way were going to check this is as follows - its same basic idea as with Paul the Octopus guesses:

  • If we subtract the regional mean from the grade mean to get the difference
  • We then want to know how likely it is that mean difference could have come from the null distribution for that sample size
  • To repeat: that null distribution is our representation of the idea that (a) the class grades and population grades could have come from the same pool of grades and (b) the sample size is 20, so we know theres going to be sampling error, if we resampled many times
  • If there was really no difference, repeated samples would have error that clustered around zero, and had some spread either side of zero

As covered in the lecture, theres an extra step we take here to make it easier to reject the null:

  • Our mean difference is standardised, in just the way we did with z-scores - except with a tweak for sample size because were standardising to the t distribution
  • We can then compare this standardised value to the t distribution directly, to see if we can reject the null
  • Ill go over this point again in a second when we have a value, just to try and be doubly clear on whats happening

So, well:

  • Compare our actual sample estimate with the t distribution wed get if there was no difference in our two means.

Lets do that manually to start with, so we can see the process, before getting R to do the work for us.

First, we know that:

  • If the null were true, and the class mean and regional mean were from the same distribution
  • And we had a sample of 20 from that, as we do here
  • Then we could see the shape of the assumed t distribution by just inputting the sample number minus one as the degrees of freedom, just as we did.

Lets see this by getting enough random samples from the t distribution to plot it, as we just did (though including a histogram of the values too):

randomsamples_from_t <- rt(n = 100000, df = length(grades)-1)

hist(randomsamples_from_t, breaks = 50, freq=F)
lines(density(randomsamples_from_t))

Now all we need to do is standardise our difference between the class and regional mean so we know what its position on the t distribution would be. We saw the maths for that in the lecture, its pretty straightforward. Symbols include:

  • \(\bar{x}\) (x-bar) is the mean for our class grades
  • \(\mu\) (mu) is the mean from the region
  • \(\hat{\sigma}\) (sigma-hat) is our sample standard deviation (wearing a hat to distinguish it from the population standard deviation, that we dont know and cant know.)

OK, lets use that formula to calculate our t value. Well break it down into parts to make it more readable, but you could of course code this all in one. (I find its generally good practice to break things down so its easier for me to read the code.)

numerator <- mean(grades) - meanofpopulation

denominator <- sd(grades)/sqrt(length(grades))

t <- numerator/denominator

t
## [1] 2.254713

So - where does this t value sit on the t distribution? Lets add it to graphic we made before. Well rerun all the code together, first getting more random samples from the t distribution, for the number of samples we have for our class grades.

Well call our random samples from t null this time, so we know were referring to what wed get if we repeatedly sampled from the null t distribution 20 twenty times over and over:

null <- rt(100000, df = length(grades)-1)

hist(null, breaks = 50, freq=F)
lines(density(null))

#Add our calculated t value
abline(v = t, lwd = 2, col='red')

Looking pretty far on the right side of the distribution. How far? Whats the probability of getting something more extreme than this value?

As before we can either actually count the number of observations, as if wed repeat-sampled from the underlying distribution:

mean(null > t)
## [1] 0.01839
  • So p = 0.01839: a 1.839% probability that, if there was no difference between the class grade mean and the regional (population) mean, you could get the value we did get, having taken 20 samples from the underlying data.

Lets just run through what just happened again one more time.

  1. We did exactly the same thing as with Paul the Octopus. There, we saw how unlikely Pauls 12 out of 14 football matches guesses would be, if the data was no better than random coin flips:

  1. We are asking whether the grade mean differs from some population mean, in this the grade average in the wider region. To do this, were asking, if they did not differ, if they came from the same underlying distribution, and we resampled many times from it - 20 samples each time - how likely would it be to get the value we did get.

Theres another key step here though. We could have done this by looking at the actual distribution of differences in means, which looks like this, with the actual grade mean on the distribution:

But instead we took the extra step of standardising the grade mean so it fits on a standard t distribution:

But: this is just a rescaling. It makes it easier to compare to the base distribution to reject the null, but its doing precisely the same thing as we saw with Paul the Octopus (though with the a different distribution), and with the non-rescaled version.

Our p value above was one-tailed: it told us the probability of getting a value more than our mean difference, if the data came from the null. But we probably want a two-tailed test here: we want to know whether we could get something as extreme as our grades on either side of the distribution, positive or negative.

We could work out the probability of both tails and sum them. Or just multiply by two (because the distributions symmetric, both tails contain the same probability.)

mean(null > t) * 2
## [1] 0.03678

And, as with pbinom, we could also use Rs mathematical version of the distribution to get a more precise value if we wanted (youll see this more accurately matches Rs t.test p value below.)

pt(q = t, df = length(grades)-1, lower.tail = F) * 2
## [1] 0.03614522

The R code version of the one-sample grades comparison

Getting R to run that for us is simple:

  1. Add the grades data
  2. Set \(\mu\) mu, which is the population mean we want to compare to (the regional grade mean in this case).
#Our manually calculated t value
t
## [1] 2.254713
#Our manually calculated two-tailed p value
pt(q = t, df = length(grades)-1, lower.tail = F) * 2
## [1] 0.03614522
#Getting R to run the t test
t.test(grades, mu = 67.5)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  grades
## t = 2.2547, df = 19, p-value = 0.03615
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 67.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  67.84422 76.75578
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##      72.3

Two sample t tests

In this section, well use a t test to compare the means from two different samples. The principles are very similar to the test we just did - the only differences here will be:

  • well use an altered equation to work out the standardised t value.
  • The output from the t test this time will show us the difference in means e.g.in its confidence intervals

First, lets load the data well use - the same height and weight data weve used before, with a couple of additions:

  1. A binary variable for earnings above $16,000 (which was the median earnings when this dataset was collected)
  2. A binary variable for angry or not
df <- read.csv(url('https://bit.ly/smi106ttest'))

Well start off by asking: are angry people shorter than non-angry people? (Which is a directional question, so we can use a one-tailed test.)

  • Note: I am unsure what this angry variable is really referring to, but this is a fun/silly example to work with, so lets stick with it

And again well work out our t-value and null distribution manually to begin with, before seeing how to stick it all in the t.test function.

Note: doing this manually can actually be very useful for making sure you know exactly what it is youre asking the test to tell you. I find it useful e.g.in this kind of case, where I need to know what polarity Im after. Otherwise just running the t-test can be a little confusing.

Heres the equation to find our t value, this time for the two-sample t-test. Note: this is for whats called a Welch two sample t-test - which R uses by default. This just means we dont assume the two samples have the same variance / the same spread of data around their means. Assuming anything else is a strong assumption, so this ways better.

The equation contains:

  • \(\bar{x}_1 - \bar{x}_2\): so thats just the mean of sample 1 minus the mean of sample 2. If its zero, theres no difference between them
  • The denominators similar to before - except this time its got the standard deviation for each sample separately, and the sample size for each separately too.

To make things a bit easier for us, lets subset the data to angry and non-angry people, so we can work with each a bit more tidily.

Note, were making a subset of the whole dataframe, so the logical operator is applying only to the rows in the first index, followed by a comma for give me all the columns.

  • Be sure to use angry_or_not, which is a binary variable, not angry (which contains seven levels).
angry <- df[df$angry_or_not==1,]

notangry <- df[df$angry_or_not==0,]

Before we find the t value, can we see any difference in height means between these two?

mean(angry$height)
## [1] 66.34286
mean(notangry$height)
## [1] 66.79307
#Subtracting them to see the difference
mean(notangry$height) - mean(angry$height)
## [1] 0.4502112

It looks like angry people are -0.4502112 inches shorter. Is is statistically significant? Lets use a t test.

Breaking down the t value calculation, that looks like the following. Well:

  • Break it down into a numerator
  • And two denominator parts
  • Before combining

Note also:

  • The effect of the order of the subtraction:
  • Heights of angry people minus heights of not-angry people:
  • If its positive, angry people are taller;
  • If its negative, angry people are shorter
numerator <- (mean(angry$height) - mean(notangry$height))

denominator1 <- sd(angry$height)^2/length(angry$height)
denominator2 <- sd(notangry$height)^2/length(notangry$height)

t <- numerator/sqrt(denominator1 + denominator2)

Note: because of the way round were finding the differences, the t value comes out as negative. Thats fine, its what we need in this case.

We have to make a new null t distribution to compare this to because the sample sizes are much bigger. Note, we compare to both sample sizes combined. Well make those separately to keep the code tidy.

samplesize <- length(angry$height) + length(notangry$height)

null <- rt(100000, df = samplesize - 1)

Now we can work out our one-tailed p value: if there was no difference between the two means, and the sample size was 1786, how likely is it wed see a different in heights less than the one we do see?

mean(null < t)
## [1] 0.00639

And of course, we could find the same thing (slightly more precisely) using pt to find the area under the probability curve. Here, we do want to find this for the lower tail, not the upper.

pt(q = t, df = samplesize -1, lower.tail = TRUE)
## [1] 0.00646903

So thats telling us:

  • If these two samples came from the same distribution, we could expect to see it showing the value we got for shorter people being angrier 0.646903% of the time, if the sampling were repeated.
  • So at, say a p value level of p < 0.05, we ** can reject the null that the mean difference we find comes from the same distribution.**

Lets run that using Rs t.test function as well. The only difference here:

  • Were entering each of the samples, where before we entered one sample and a mu value for the assumed population mean.
  • We can also tell the t.test that we want a particular tail. alternative = 'less' tells it to use the lower tail.
t.test(angry$height, notangry$height, alternative = 'less')
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  angry$height and notangry$height
## t = -2.488, df = 1756.1, p-value = 0.00647
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##        -Inf -0.1524093
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  66.34286  66.79307

Though if we tell it which tail to use, we dont get very useful confidence intervals. So we could just leave alternative blank, and halve the p-value if we want a one-tailed test:

t.test(angry$height, notangry$height)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  angry$height and notangry$height
## t = -2.488, df = 1756.1, p-value = 0.01294
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.80512140 -0.09530091
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  66.34286  66.79307

As always - the p value and confidence intervals are two sides of the same coin:

  • The p value tells us we can reject the null (assuming we decided our p cutoff was p < 0.05)
  • The 95% confidence interval does not include zero, so the model is ruling out the difference in means being above or below zero.

Visualising a t-test with the dabestr package

One quick way to see what a t-test is showing is to use the dabestr package. Lets install it, and any dependencies. You can install in the usual way:

install.packages('dabestr')

Then load the library:

library(dabestr)
## Warning: package 'dabestr' was built under R version 4.0.5
## Loading required package: magrittr
## Warning: package 'magrittr' was built under R version 4.0.5

Note: loading the library may not work as there may be some missing dependencies that will also need to be installed. Try it, and well look to see what libraries are missing.

Once installed, we can use it to visualise our angry / not-angry / height data. Note though:

  • dabestr takes in the full dataframe, and we just specify the data column (height) and the category column (angry_or_not).
  • It may take a little while to run as its using bootstrapping simulation to get its results.
  • (We wont cover bootstrapping in this module: for now, just note its a way to use simulation to work out confidence intervals and other inferential stats.)
# The idx below passes "Control" as the control group, 
# and "Group1" as the test group. The mean difference
# will be computed as mean(Group1) - mean(Control1).
two.group.unpaired <- dabest(df, angry_or_not, height, 
         idx = c("0", "1"), 
         paired = FALSE)

two.group.unpaired.meandiff <- mean_diff(two.group.unpaired)

# Calling the above object produces a textual summary of the computed effect size.
two.group.unpaired.meandiff
## dabestr (Data Analysis with Bootstrap Estimation in R) v0.3.0
## =============================================================
## 
## Good evening!
## The current time is 12:40 PM on Thursday November 18, 2021.
## 
## Dataset    :  df
## X Variable :  angry_or_not
## Y Variable :  height
## 
## Unpaired mean difference of 1 (n = 805) minus 0 (n = 981)
##  -0.45 [95CI  -0.795; -0.0863]
## 
## 
## 5000 bootstrap resamples.
## All confidence intervals are bias-corrected and accelerated.
#Make the plot
plot(two.group.unpaired.meandiff)

A few things to note there:

  • The output from two.group.unpaired.meandiff:
  • The confidence intervals are similar to the t.test above, though slightly different because bootstrapped.)
  • The graphic makes it a little difficult to see if theres a difference - because the difference is very small relative to the spread of the data. In combination with how close the upper bound of the confidence intervals are to zero, this is suggesting a small effect size.

The full regression output from R

Lastly, lets look at the full summary output from a simple regression model so we can see how to make inference readings from it, and how to easily access confidence intervals.

Well re-use the same data weve just been using.

A sometimes useful function is attach: if we attach a dataframe, we no longer have to use its full name (such as df$height) but can instead just use height.

Its not great if youre working with many dataframes that may have matching column names, but it sometimes helps keep things tidy. Lets do that for our current data.

attach(df)
## The following object is masked _by_ .GlobalEnv:
## 
##     angry
x <- lm(weight ~ height + age + male)

summary(x)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = weight ~ height + age + male)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -91.905 -18.477  -4.749  11.608 185.366 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -136.67906   16.31765  -8.376  < 2e-16 ***
## height         4.12922    0.24802  16.649  < 2e-16 ***
## age            0.32030    0.03913   8.186 5.09e-16 ***
## male          11.13628    1.94909   5.714 1.29e-08 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 28.11 on 1782 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3389, Adjusted R-squared:  0.3378 
## F-statistic: 304.5 on 3 and 1782 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Ill run back through all the elements of this in the lecture slides, to remind us.

Theres a handy function for getting confidence intervals for all our model coefficients:

confint(x)
##                   2.5 %       97.5 %
## (Intercept) -168.682811 -104.6753115
## height         3.642782    4.6156589
## age            0.243557    0.3970406
## male           7.313542   14.9590121

By default it outputs 95% confidence intervals, but we can also set our own:

confint(x, level = 0.99)
##                    0.5 %      99.5 %
## (Intercept) -178.7556169 -94.6025061
## height         3.4896816   4.7687597
## age            0.2194034   0.4211942
## male           6.1103808  16.1621732

Note what happens there when we increase the value of the confidence interval: the intervals get wider, as they have to cover more data to be 99% sure the true parameter is within its bounds.

Visualising regression coefficients

Well look at ways to output regression tables another time, but today lets stick to visualising coefficients.

There are a few options for plotting, but a quick one is to use the jtools library. Again, install this library first:

install.packages('jtools')

Then load the library:

library(jtools)
## Warning: package 'jtools' was built under R version 4.0.5

Then its just a simple case of dropping our model (assigned to x earlier) into jtools. Note, were also:

  • Choosing a colour palette for it
  • Setting the confidence intervals to 0.99
jtools::plot_coefs(x,ci_level = .99, colors = "Rainbow")

We can see that age doesnt show up very well, so we could transform it, so it becomes in units of 10 years.

EXERCISE: Have a go at doing this yourself. Transform the age variable - creating a new one in the df dataframe called something like age_tenyears by (a) dividing df$age by ten and assigning to a new column in df. Youll then need to re-attach df if you want to use just plain column names as before. Then (b) re-run the lm model to include the new variable and (c) visualise the coefficients again with jtools.

Lets also quickly look at how to output someting similar using ggplot, so you can use all the control you have with ggplot, if you want to change anything yourself. We have a few steps to do.

  1. Make a dataframe with the regression coefficients and the confidence intervals, so we can use that in ggplot
  2. Use ggplots geom_errorbar function to add confidence intervals to the plot

First - making the dataframe:

  1. We make a column for the coefficients
  2. We cbind (column bind) this to the confidence intervals, just using the confint function we used before.
  3. We add the coefficient names in to the data frame so ggplot can use them.
df.viz <- data.frame(coefficients = x$coefficients)

df.viz <- cbind(
  df.viz,
  confint(x)
)

df.viz$names = row.names(df.viz)

Lastly, we drop the intercept row as we dont want to visualise that:

df.viz <- df.viz[-1,]

Take a look at the resulting dataframe before we use it to plot. Its got everything together:

df.viz

Now we can use ggplot to plot our coefficients and the error bars around them. Well also need to load the tidyverse.

library(tidyverse)

ggplot(df.viz, aes(y = coefficients, x = names)) +
  geom_point(size = 5) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = `2.5 %`, ymax = `97.5 %`), width = 0.1) +
  coord_flip()
